-- в”Ђв”Ђ JumpCloud в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Cloud directory platform unifying identity, device management, SSO and MFA for modern IT teams.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free for up to 10 users, paid plans from $9/user/month$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2012, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$501-1000 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Louisville, Colorado, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$JumpCloud Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$JumpCloud review 2026: cloud directory, SSO, MFA and device management platform. Compare pricing tiers, features, pros, cons and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$JumpCloud is a cloud-based directory platform, headquartered in Louisville, Colorado, that unifies identity, device, and access management for both human and non-human (service account, API, machine) identities. The company was founded in 2012 by Rajat Bhargava and Alex Fagundes, initially built as a modern, cloud-native alternative to Microsoft's on-premises Active Directory, positioning itself as an 'Open Directory Platform' that works across Windows, macOS, and Linux and integrates with cloud infrastructure such as AWS, Google Workspace, Microsoft 365, and thousands of SaaS applications via SAML and SCIM. JumpCloud's core architecture centers on a cloud directory that authenticates and authorizes users, then layers on single sign-on (SSO), multi-factor authentication (MFA), mobile device management (MDM) for laptops and mobile devices, LDAP-as-a-service, RADIUS-as-a-service, a password manager, conditional access policies, and directory insights/reporting. In more recent years the company has added Zero Trust security capabilities and AI- and SaaS-management features aimed at giving IT teams visibility into shadow SaaS usage and unmanaged devices. JumpCloud has raised a total of approximately $462 million across multiple rounds, starting with a $1.2 million seed round in December 2012, a $3 million Series A in January 2014, a $4.3 million Series B in 2015, a $20 million Series C in November 2017, a $50 million Series D in May 2019, and a Series E that closed at $100 million (an initial $75 million tranche in November 2020 followed by an additional $25 million in January 2021); the company reached a $2.63 billion valuation following an October 2021 funding round led by Sapphire Ventures and BlackRock. JumpCloud filed for and later withdrew IPO plans, remaining a private company with reported ARR in the range of roughly $200 million and around 900 employees as of 2026. Pricing is structured as a generous free tier covering up to 10 users with core identity and device management features, an a la carte model where individual features (Device Management, SSO, Cloud Directory, MFA, User Lifecycle Management, Password Manager, Cloud LDAP/RADIUS, Conditional Access) can be purchased individually starting around $3-6/user/month when billed annually, and a Device Management package at $9/user/month, an SSO package at $11/user/month, and a combined Device Identity Management package at $13/user/month, alongside bundled Platform Essentials (capped at 300 users), Platform, and Platform Prime tiers priced via custom quote for organizations wanting a fully unified identity, device and security stack. JumpCloud primarily targets IT administrators and MSPs at small and mid-sized businesses that want to avoid the cost and complexity of on-premises Active Directory or a fragmented stack of point identity tools. Its most direct competitors are Microsoft Entra ID (Azure AD), Okta, Google Workspace's identity layer, OneLogin, and Rippling's IT/device management module; JumpCloud differentiates through its cross-platform (Windows/Mac/Linux) directory-first approach, its granular a la carte pricing that lets smaller companies pay only for the modules they need, and its focus on unifying both human and non-human identity management under one console.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'e87fc9fe-9139-4e2a-b348-1b4b64fe9eeb';

